otential proliferators? Does the country’s championing of arms control and disarmament on the global stage matter? What about the domestic costs of nuclear technologies and atomic research, including their impact on local communities and the environment? The contributors to this important collection consider how the atomic age has shaped Canadian policies at home and abroad. Their incisive assessment of the country’s nuclear history engages with much larger debates about national identity, Canadian foreign policy contradictions during the Cold War, and Canada’s place in the international order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCold War. 0aNuclear energyxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aNuclear weaponsxGovernment policyzCanada. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aColbourn, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColbourn, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCunningham, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDean, Ryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJang, Se Young, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLackenbauer, P. Whitney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKercher, Asa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSayle, Timothy Andrews, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSayle, Timothy Andrews, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStevenson, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiseman, Matthew S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe 